  • Introduction

Introduction¶

The TMDb movie dataset from kaggle was selected for this project. This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including metrics about how successful these movies are (e.g. popularity, revenue and vote-average) as well as some basic information of the movie (e.g. cast, director, keywords, runtime, genres, etc.). The purpose of this project is to go through the general data analysis process and identify properties that are associated with the success of movies as well as some interesting trends, such as genre trends, over years. I am going to explore the dataset by answering the following research questions:

Part One -- General Explore:

  1. Which genre/production company/director has the highest release of movies?
  2. What's the total budget from year to year?
  3. What's the total revenue from year to year?
  4. What's the total profit from year to year?

Part Two -- Analysis of Categorical Variables:

  1. Which genres have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?
  2. Which directors direct the movies that have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?
  3. Which production companies produce movies that have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?

Part Three -- Analysis of Numerical Variables:

  1. What kinds of properties are associated with high revenues?
  2. What kinds of properties are associated with high profit?

Step 1 -- Check for missing data, only keep columns that are needed for analysis. Check and drop duplicates.¶

An overview of the dataset shows that the data types are appropriate. But there is a significant amount of missing data for columns such as homepage, tagline, keywords, and production_companies. We decides to drop "homepage" and "tagline" which are of irrelevant in answering the research questions, while keeping "keywords" and "production_companies" for potential analysis.

The dataset contains "budget", "revenue", "budget_adj" and "revenue_adj", where the later two columns - "budget_adj" and "revenue_adj" show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time. The adjusted budget and revenue are more accurate in comparing the profit over year. Therefore, I decide to drop the redundent columns - "budget" and "revenue", and keep only "budget_adj" and "revenue_adj".

Step 2 -- Identify and modify rows which contain incorrect or inappropriate values.¶

By looking into the concise summery of the dataset, I noticed that there are lots of movies where the budget (5695 rows) or revenue (6016 rows) have a value of '0' which means that the values of those variables of those movies have not been recorded. Calculating the profits of these movies would lead to inappropriate results. Considering the large amount of these movie data, dropping all the rows with '0' budget or revenue may influence the accuracy of analysing the trends and categorical variables, I decide to replace zero values with null values in the budget and revenue column.

In [14]:
# Replace zero values with null values in the budget and revenue column.
df['budget_adj'] = df['budget_adj'].replace(0, np.NaN)
df['revenue_adj'] = df['revenue_adj'].replace(0, np.NaN)
# see if nulls are added in budget and revenue columns
df.info()

Popularity per movie

In [77]:
# function of plotting performance per movie
def performance_mean(filename, factor):
    if filename == 'genres':
        per_mean = df_split_genres
    elif filename == 'production_companies':
        per_mean = df_split_production_companies
    elif filename == 'director':
        per_mean = df_split_director
    per_mean = per_mean[[filename,factor]].groupby(filename).mean()
    per_mean = per_mean.sort_values(by=factor, ascending=False).head(20)
    # plot the bar chart
    per_mean.plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (15,10))
    plt.xlabel(filename)
    plt.ylabel(factor)
    plt.title('Top 20 ' + filename.title() + ' with Highest ' + factor.title() + ' per Movie')
    plt.show()
In [68]:
performance_mean('genres', 'popularity')

Total popularity

In [78]:
# function of plotting total performance
def performance_sum(filename, factor):
    if filename == 'genres':
        per_sum = df_split_genres
    elif filename == 'production_companies':
        per_sum = df_split_production_companies
    elif filename == 'director':
        per_sum = df_split_director
    per_sum = per_sum[[filename,factor]].groupby(filename).sum()
    per_sum = per_sum.sort_values(by=factor, ascending=False).head(20)
    # plot the bar chart
    per_sum.plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (15,10))
    plt.xlabel(filename)
    plt.ylabel(factor)
    plt.title('Top 20 ' + filename.title() + ' with Highest Total ' + factor.title())
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

The results of this investigation are discussed in the following three parts

Part One -- Interesting Trends:¶

1. Which genre/production company/director has the highest release of movies?¶

Drama (4760), Comedy (3793), Thriller (2907), Action (2384) and Romance (1712) are the top 5 genres that have the highest release of movies, being produced by the most productive production companies such as Universal Pictures (522), Warner Bros. (509), Paramount Pictures (431), Twentieth Century Fox Film Corporation (282), and Columbia Pictures (272) etc. The most productive directors are Woody Allen (46), Clint Eastwood (34), Martin Scorsese (31), Steven Spielberg (30) and Steven Soderbeigh (23) as the top 5.

2. What's the total budget from year to year?¶

The total budget of movies generally increased from year to year, with a rapid rise from 1994 to 1999 and reached the perk in 2010 with around 9.3 billion budget invested.

3. What's the total revenue from year to year?¶

The total revenue continuously increased over years and reach its maximum in 2015 at 25 billion.

4. What's the total profit from year to year?¶

The total profit of movies has the similar trend as the total revenue and reach the maximum in 2015 at 17.5 billion

Part Two -- Analysis of Categorical Variables:¶

Genre, director, and production company are the three categorical variables we are interested to investigate. We do the analysis one by one and by calculating both the average performance per movie and the total performance.

1. Which genres have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?¶

When popularity per movie is calculated, the most popular genres are Adventure, Science Fiction, Fantasy, Action, and Animation. While when the total popularity is calculated, Drama, Comedy, Action, Thriller and Adventure are the top genres. The difference may lies in the high release number of Drama and Comedy despite their relatively low popularity per movie. Documentary, Music, History, Animation, and War are the top 5 genres which have the highest vote-rating per movie. But for total vote-rating, Drama, Comedy, Thriller, Action, and Romance become the top performers due to the large release number. When considering the revenue of individual movie, Animation, Adventure, Fantasy, Family and Science Fiction are the top genres. When it comes to the total revenue, Action, Adventure, Drama, Comedy, and Thriller climb up to the top of the ranking. The result shows that Animation used to be the top-grossing movie, although it has a relatively low release. The chart of profit show the similar result as the chart of revenue. The main difference is that for total revenue, Actions perform better and Adventures, while for total profit, Adventures perform better than Actions. One possible explanation is that the Actions tend to require higher budget than Adventures did.

2. Which directors direct the movies that have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?¶

Colin Trevorrow, David Leitch, Chad Stahelski, Juno John Lee and Alan Taylor are the top 5 directors who have the highest popularity per move. For total popularity, the top 5 directors are Christopher Nolan, Steven Spielberg, Quentin Tarantino, Peter Jackson and Ridley Scott. There is no significant difference among directors in terms of vote-rating per movie. For the total vote-rating, Woody Allen performed much better than the others, followed by Clint Eastwood, Martin Scorsese, Steven Spielberg, and Ridley Scott When it comes to revenue, Irwin Winkler, Clyde Geronimi, Hamilton Luske, Jennifer Lee, and George Lucas are the top 5 directors who have the highest revenue per movie. After taking into account the release number of directors, Steven Spielberg, Steven Spielberg performed much better than the other directors. The total revenue of movies directed by him is twice the amount of the second director. The results for profit are almost the same as those for revenue. Thus, we are not going to go through it in detail.

3. Which Production Companies produce movies that have the highest popularity/vote-rating/revenue/profit?¶

The analysis of production companies reveals that producers associated with high popularity movies are Warner Bros., Universal Pictures and Paramount Bulletproof Cupid, Fuji Television Network, and DefyNite Films are the producers that have the highest popularity per movie. The vote-ratings per movie are almost the same among producers. For the revenue/profit per movie, Hoya Productions, Truenorth Productions, Alfran Productions are the tops three producers. When the number of release is taken into account, Warner Bros., Universal Pictures, and Paramount Pictures are the top producers for all the four metrics.

Part Three -- Analysis of Numerical Variables:¶

1. What kinds of properties are associated with high revenues?¶

By calculating the correlation matrix and plotting the scatter chart, we find that popularity and budget are moderately associated with revenue.

2. What kinds of properties are associated with high profit?¶

The correlation matrix and scatter chart show that popularity is moderately associated with profit.

Limitations¶

First, the way I deal with inaccurate and unreasonable data can be further discussed. There is a large number of zero values in revenue and budget. I replace them with nulls. However, I randomly picked some of them and searched online, these data are actually available. With these values being rectified, the analysis will be more accurate.

Second, the lack of information on how popularity and vote-rating were calculated limit the current analysis. Knowing more about how these metrics are calculated can help us make better judgement on when and how to use these data. For example, how to deal with zero values or outliers of them.

Third, the methods and skills covered by the course so far is very limited, more detailed and advanced analysis are required to reveal more useful and inspiring findings. For example, time series analysis are expected to describe the trends of movie industry, and correlation analysis is needed to show delicate relationship between factors.
